sses are initialized. It seems that many classes are initialized at runtime, especially for third-party libraries, unless they're proven to be safe. If it’s runtime, reflection usually requires metadata, but I wonder if the dynamic access report can recognize those calls. GraalVM can automatically detect certain reflections and register them, but perhaps not all targets, even constants. I’m considering using the existing build cache for compilation issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test compilation issues**\\n\\nThe user has made it clear not to compile or run tests myself, so I'll avoid that. I should probably check `build/reports/tests`, although that might not be relevant. I'm thinking about potential issues, like needing an active dynamic-access class in its own dedicated Scala test file. Also, I need to ensure that all top-level test classes are public, and `class ExtensionSchemasTest` is indeed public in Scala. I should also watch for packages outside the library.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented a dedicated Scala coverage test for `org.apache.pekko.protobufv3.internal.ExtensionSchemas`.\n\nChanged:\n- Added `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-protobuf-v3_3/1.0.1/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_protobuf_v3_3/ExtensionSchemasTest.scala`\n\nWhat it does:\n- Defines a minimal proto2-style `GeneratedMessageV3` test message.\n- Calls the protected generated-message merge path through a public subclass method.\n- This naturally drives schema creation for a full-runtime proto2 generated message, which reaches `ExtensionSchemas.full()` and the remaining dynamic-access path in `loadSchemaForFullRuntime`.\n- Keeps the test outside the library package and avoids direct reflection.\n\nPer instruction, I did not compile or run tests locally.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a9405780718f88d0169f3beb933ac8192926fa0a2afa21b12\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.